# ESLint Best Practices

## Context

- Applies to all JavaScript and TypeScript files
- Ensures code quality and consistency
- Maintains Next.js and React coding standards

## Critical Rules

- Use the recommended ESLint configuration for Next.js projects
- Enable TypeScript support in ESLint for type checking
- Regularly update ESLint and plugins to benefit from latest rules
- Integrate ESLint with your editor for real-time feedback
- Create custom rules to enforce project-specific coding standards
- Fix linting errors before committing code
- Use consistent formatting and naming conventions
- Implement proper error handling patterns

## Examples

<example>
  // ✅ DO: Follow ESLint rules and use proper naming
  const handleUserClick = (userId: string): void => {
    if (!userId) return;
    
    try {
      navigateToUser(userId);
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Navigation failed:', error);
    }
  };
</example>

